main event: A slow-moving object was tracked on radar at Yuma, Arizona on February 27, 1961.
interesting points: The object's presentation on radar was similar to that of a single aircraft, but it began to break up and become diffused at around 42,223 feet.
Despite moving at only 29 knots, the object left a trail of diffuse echoes extending behind it, similar to a stream of chaff.
The rate of descent of the object was approximately 323 feet per minute until contact was lost.
The officer who prepared the report had not encountered a similar radar presentation, except for chaff dropped from balloons in Alaska.
The report concludes that the data is inadequate for evaluation, and the object remains unidentified.
witnesses: Radar operators at the 664th ACWRON USMC ALS Station
